<br>
As it stands now, Flowing Thoughts items will stack, up to a maximum of 15 mana/tick.  That's not bad, and doesn't take a buff slot(can't be dispelled), and stacks with the other mana regen spell effects.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately, pre-Luclin, we had these available only from:<br>
Cazic Thule<br>
ToV named mobs<br>
Coldain Prayer Shawl 7(runed coldain prayer shawl)<br>
<br>
That was it.  On Luclin, it almost seems that most boss mobs(the level 60+ ones) all have a chance to drop a flowing thoughts item.<br>
<br>
I agree that the mana cost on spells is a bit high, which is why spellcasting mastery(Arch AA ability) is so good, it improves our chance to make a specialization check, which drops the mana cost on our spells.<br>
<br>
Crits are also good with the AA abilities, but I agree, why should we need to spend AA points for something that should be considered a normal ability?  In all fairness, wizards should get an inherant spell casting fury at lower levels as a part of class balance.<br>
<br>
For casters with an int(or wis) over 200, we should get what melees get, the ability to ALWAYS be able to cast a spell, though perhaps with a longer cast time(50 percent longer to cast the spell?).<br>
<br>
As it stands, we have downtime if we group or not, so why not balance us so that we get the same perks that melees get that ALLOW them to continually swing that heavy sword?  Why shouldn't we get crits with our spells without needing to spend AA points?<br>
<br>
Now, if this is asking too much, even dropping the min level on spells between 10 and 20 levels worth would also solve many issues since we are always mana limited.<br>
 <p>Targonis Manastorm<br>
Level 60 Wizard<br>
The Nameless Server<br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ufraethir.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Fraethir</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_bluespot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/3/02 10:07:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=674.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Things I would like to see for casters (very long)</span><hr size=1> FT items being available on Luclin boss mobs doesn't make them terribly available to non-L60-raiding-wizards.<br>
<br>
Actually fixing casters needs to be something that's done across the board, not for the limited part of the population that can take down the THO, or Rhag' or Arch Liche or whatever. FT1 items (which can't stack with themselves) should be more obtainable for more 'normal' wizards, if they're going to be consider class enhancing/fixing.<br>
<br>
I tend to agree on generic 'wizards can crit on spells allatime' idea, much like warriors can crit. The problem I see with it is that casters aren't as easily directly comparable as melees. Warriors were the baseline everyone else is compared to. I can't think of any easy way to compare casters. If anything, it'd be something like 'mages are DD baseline. Wizards are supposed to be able to do 120% of mages in DD' sort of things, much like 'warriors are baseline. Monks do this much more, rogues situationally do this much more'.<br>
With casters, you can't rely on damage, because of utility spells and what flavor of damage it is (pet, DD, DoT), special effects added to the damage (stunning, interrupting, debuffing), or mode of the damage (bolt, single target, rain, 4 target aoe, pbaoe). The different caster classes each have strong suits and weak ones, and might be the baseline for DoT single target, or something... but drawing the lines for that would be really subjective. By the way, wizards aren't (or shouldn't be) baseline for ANY form of damage. Wizards, from description and design, exceed the baseline across the board (faster damage, better efficiency, efficiency in pbaoe, etc).<br>
